%S A079772 6,8,10,12,12,14,16,18,18,20,22,24,24,26,30,28,30,30,32,34,36,36,40,
%T A079772 38,40,42,42,44,46,48,48,50,56,52,54,54,56,60,58,60,60,62,64,66,66,70,
%U A079772 68,70,72,72,74,76,78,78,84,80,82,84,84,86,90,88,90,90,92,98,94,96,96,100
%N A079772 Let C(n) be the n-th composite number; then a(n) is the smallest number > C(n) and not coprime to C(n).
%C A079772 For n >= 1, if p = A020639(A002808(n)) = A056608(n), then a(n) = A002808(n) + p satisfies a(n) - p = A002808(n) and p divides a(n). In contrast with A085271, the first term a(1) = 6 is already composite. It corresponds to A002808(1) = 4 and satisfies 6 - 2 = 4. - _Charles Kusniec_, Jul 03 2026
%F A079772 a(n) = C(n) + smallest prime divisor of C(n).
%F A079772 a(n) = A002808(n) + A056608(n). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jan 31 2003
%F A079772 n + n/log n + n/log^2 n < a(n) < n + n/log n + 4n/log^2 n for n >= 4. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jul 05 2026
%e A079772 C(4) = 9 and C(5) = 10 hence a(4) = a(5) = 12.
%e A079772 For 91=7*13 we have 91+7 = 98; for 92=2*2*23 we have 92+2 = 94.
%e A079772 Since A002808(15) = 25 and A020639(25) = 5, we have a(15) = 25 + 5 = 30. Thus, a(15) - 5 = 25, and 5 divides both 25 and a(15). Here, 30 = 5*(5 + 1) is the upper oblong adjacent to 25 = 5^2.
%o A079772 (PARI) cminusp31(n) = { for(x=2,n, forprime(p=2,floor(sqrt(x)), if(x%p==0 & isprime(x)==0, print1(x+p,", "); break); ) ) }
%Y A079772 Cf. A002808, A056608.
%Y A079772 Cf. A020639, A036690, A085271 (difference between the n-th composite number and its smallest prime divisor).
%K A079772 nonn,changed
%O A079772 1,1
%A A079772 _Amarnath Murthy_, Jan 31 2003
%E A079772 More terms from _Cino Hilliard_, Aug 12 2003
